Ellsworth Community School is seeking to hire a part-time Athletic Director. Duties include;

Game management at all home events
Supervision and evaluation of coaches and athletic teams
Interaction with parents, players, and coaches
General athletic event organization and management

All scheduling of referees and games are handled separately and would not fall under that AD's direct responsibilities.

Annual $10,000 contact. Please contact Superintendent, Aaron Gaffney at agaffney@ellsworth.k12.mi.us for more information.

Sports are back at ECS. Today the MHSAA approved volleyball competition for schools in Regions 6 and 8.

However, indoor events are subject to strict maximum spectator capacities. In the case of ECS we will be limited to 25% of our gym's capacity, which equates to 100 individuals. This number includes players, coaches, officials, scorekeepers, school personnel, and spectators.

We anticipate only being able to accommodate approximately 60 spectators, split evenly between the two competing schools. As a result we will be limiting entry to player's immediate families only.

All spectators will be required to maintain social distancing and wear facial coverings at all times. There will be no…

Cross Country Update - The first day of Boys/Girls Cross Country practice will be Wednesday, August 12 at 6:00 p.m. Please plan on meeting outside the high school gym lobby.

ECS is excited to announce that we have hired Robin Sommer as the new head Boys/Girls Cross Country Coach. In addition ECS Alumni and collegiate runners Winter Romeyn and Nate Veldboom will be acting as assistant coaches for this fall's season as both are temporarily in the area working remotely. We are excited to welcome Coach Sommer to the ECS family and equally excited to welcome back Winter and Nate. We know that their collective running wisdom will be extremely valuable for our runners.

ECS Update: Attention parents of students in grades 6-12 planning on participating in Athletics this fall (Middle School Basketball, High School Cross Country, JV/Varsity Volleyball, MS Football, HS Football.)

Any student who has a physical on file with the school from last year (2019/20) does NOT need a new physical. There is a simple two page form for parents to complete prior to participation. (https://www.mhsaa.com/portals/0/Documents/health%20safety/healthquestionnaire.pdf)

If your student does not have a sports physical on file from last year they will need one before the first day of practice. (https://www.mhsaa.com/portals/0/Documents/health%20safety/physical4page.pdf)

Please contact Ms. Murray at smurray@ellsworth.k12.mi.us for sports physical information.

post_text:
Graduation Update

ECS will be celebrating the graduating Class of 2020 on Friday, June 5 with a family only outdoor commencement ceremony. This family only event will be followed by a public graduation parade at 6:40 p.m.

ECS asks that community, extended family, and friends respect the graduates and their immediate families and refrain from gathering at the school during the actual "family only ceremony." Instead we encourage those that would like to cheer on the graduates to line the parade route.

The parade will run from the elementary ball field, up main street before turning and ending near the Ellsworth Farmers Exchange. ECS would like to encourage all those lining the parade route to respect social distancing guidelines.

Kolby Louis Krosnicki, son of Lisa and Carl Krosnicki, is a determined member of the class of 2020. Kolby’s hobbies include skiing, running, and baseball. At ECS Kolby was a member of NHS and a mentor in the Little Buddies program.

In addition to this, Kolby represented ECS on the Cross Country and Baseball teams. Kolby’s favorite class at ECS is Chemistry because he feels it, “teaches students how the world is built and how it works.”

Kolby is most proud of keeping his G.P.A. above a 3.5 as a multi-sport athlete. After graduation, Kolby plans to attend college at Appalachian State University.

Kolby’s favorite quote- “I’m glad I’m a revelation and not a disappointment.” -Maggie Smith

Branden R VanderSlik, son of Jodi and Keith VanderSlik, is a tenacious member of the class of 2020. Branden’s hobbies include fishing, eating, and sleeping.

Branden had difficulty choosing his favorite class at ECS, but he is certain that he enjoyed spending lunch with his friends. Throughout high school, Branden could be found behind the scenes of many projects. He has been an integral auxiliary member of maintenance for ECS.

Branden is most proud of graduating and finishing school. He has worked hard and is looking forward to his future.

Speaking of the future, after graduation Branden plans to get his Commercial Drivers License.

post_text:
TJ Michael Schultz, son of Mary Drenth and Todd Schultz, is a competitive member of the class of 2020. TJ’s hobbies include two-tracking, working on vehicles, hunting, and fishing.

In addition to this, he enjoys spending time riding dirt bikes, ATVs, and snowmobiles. TJ was a member of the ECS Baseball team. Moreover, he was a member of the State Championship Football team. TJ also found time to play Hockey and was a member of the Squirt Year State Championship team.

TJ’s favorite class was Welding. TJ is most proud of successfully making it through Army Basic Training at Fort Sill. After graduation, TJ plans to go to Fort Leonard Wood for Army Advanced Individual Training (AIT) in Diesel Mechanics.

TJ’s favorite quote- “You miss 100% of the shots you don’t take.” - Wayne Gretzky

Jesse Maxwell Hersha, son of Julie and Frank Hersha, is a pragmatic member of the class of 2020.

As an avid sportsman, Jesse enjoys hunting and fishing. Jesse has represented ECS on the Baseball, Basketball, and Football teams. In addition to this, he was a mentor in the Little Buddies program. Jesse’s favorite class is History.

Jesse enjoys history because “it gives us the opportunity to learn from past mistakes, explains why we act the way we act, why we are the way we are, and how we got to be that way.” Jesse is most proud of being a member of the Conference Championship teams in Basketball and Baseball. In addition, he earned 1st Team All-Conference in Baseball for each year of high school.

After he graduates, Jesse plans to join the Air Force.

Jesse’s favorite quote- “The harder the conflict, the greater the triumph.” - George Washington

McKenzie Lee Essenberg, daughter of Charlene and Corey Essenberg is a competitive member of the class of 2020. McKenzie’s hobbies include playing sports, spending time with friends, and being with her family.

McKenzie has represented ECS on the Volleyball, Basketball, and Softball teams. In addition to this, McKenzie is a member of the National Honor Society. McKenzie’s favorite class at ECS is Chemistry because she enjoys the challenge and working with other students.

McKenzie is most proud of keeping a high G.P.A. throughout high school while playing a sport every season. After she graduates, McKenzie plans to attend college and pursue a degree in Sonography.

McKenzie’s favorite quote - “Learn to value yourself, which means: fight for your happiness.”- Ayn Rand

Brianna Rayne Host, daughter of Veronica Dorcey and Ali Jensenius, is a dynamic member of the class of 2020. Brianna’s hobbies include playing the piano, being with her family, and spending time with friends.

During her time at ECS Brianna was a member of the Spirit Squad and the National Honor Society. Brianna’s favorite subject is World History. This is because she has had a passion for different cultures and how they are intertwined with each other.

Brianna is most proud of completing her 9th and 10th-grade credits within one year. After Graduation, Brianna plans to attend college to major in Psychology and minor in Early Childhood Education.

Brianna's favorite quote -“I believe that everything happens for a reason. People change so that you can learn to let go, things go wrong so that you appreciate them when they’re right. You believe lies so that you eventually learn to trust no one but yourself and sometimes good things fall apart so better things can fall together.”- Marilyn Monroe

post_text:
Remote Learning PBIS

Dear ECS Elementary Families:

Over the course of the last two school years Ellsworth Elementary has been actively engaged in developing a PBIS (Positive Behavior Interventions & Supports) program for students in grades K-5. Our program, which focuses on our three Lancer Values (Value Safety, Value Others, and Value Self), has been tremendously successful in creating a positive climate and culture in our school building. Through the active teaching of expected behaviors, the recognition and rewarding of positive student actions, and constant reteaching of established daily routines we have made great strides in making the Lancer Values an expected part of school life at… More

post_text:
Sarah Rose VanderArk, daughter of Kim and Brad VanderArk, is an innovative member of the class of 2020. Sarah loves to draw, write stories, cook various food substances, and edit videos & pictures.

Sarah is a member of the National Honor Society and a mentor in the Little Buddies Program. In addition to this, Sarah has been an adjunct member of the Student Council. Over her years in high school, she has made countless posters for pep assemblies and pitched in for events. She adores Art because she gets to do something she cares about! She states, “managing to turn ideas and feelings into the visual form will never cease to be fun for my bones”. Sarah is most proud that she is in existence and managed to make it through her high school career.

After Graduation, Sarah plans to attend the College for Creative Studies to study Entertainment Arts. When she completes her degree she plans to work in Movie/ Television Production.

Sarah's favorite quote -"It's like poetry, it's sort of, they rhyme." - George Lucas

post_text:
Robert Lyman Wise, son of Doreen and Robert Wise, is a driven member of the class of 2020. Robbie has represented ECS on the Cross Country, Baseball, and Track & Field teams. In addition to this, he is a member of the National Honor Society, Student Council, SAFE in Northern Michigan, Demolay, and a mentor in the Little Buddies program.

Robbie’s hobbies include running, fishing, exercising, and spending time with people he loves. Robbie’s favorite class at ECS is Chemistry because “it teaches us how our world is built and how our world works”. Robbie is most proud of his running career. He is happy to have run a 16:50 5k and has his name on the Ellsworth Record board.

After graduation, Robbie plans to attend North Central Michigan College full time. He plans to earn a degree in Business Management. After that, he would like to open up his own small business.

Robbie’s favorite quote - “We keep moving forward, opening up new doors and doing new things… and curiosity keeps leading us down new paths.”
–Walt Disney

First and foremost I want to emphasize that this is a “remote learning” plan. This is not an online education plan. While there are most certainly components that will be more easily accessed through the use of technology, we are committed to making…

Thursday, April 2

ECS Families;

Good morning. As many of you have now read and watched Governor Whitmer has suspended face-to-face K-12 instruction for the remainder of the 2019/20 school year. This is an announcement that the ECS team has been anticipating for the past two weeks. As a result we already have many preliminary plans in place that we will be communicating out to families early next week.

However, at this time what I want to assure to all of our families and students is that the teachers and staff of ECS are committed to making the best of a terrible situation. We will be working closely with everyone to put out the best educational product that we can under this difficult…

Caleb Gregory Godwin, son of Nancy and Cary Godwin, is a creative member of the class of 2020.

Caleb has represented ECS on the Cross Country, Basketball, Track & Field, and Quiz Bowl teams. In addition to this, He is a member of the National Honor Society and Little Buddies program.

Caleb’s hobbies include skiing, skating, and making some form of art. Caleb’s favorite class at ECS is Mathematics with U.S. History a close second. Caleb is most proud of becoming the person he has always wanted to be.

After graduation, Caleb plans to attend Northern Michigan University. While in Marquette getting his education, Caleb intends to focus on skiing too.

Caleb’s favorite quote - “That hurt really bad you’re a fool if you think I’m not trying again!” - Quinn Wolfermann

Ethan Christopher Tornga, son of Annette and Chris Tornga, is the Salutatorian of the class of 2020.

Ethan’s hobbies include basketball and hanging out with friends. Ethan has represented ECS on the Basketball, and Track & Field teams. In addition to this, Ethan is the president of the National Honor Society, a member of Safe in Northern Michigan, and a mentor in the Little Buddies program.

Ethan’s favorite class is Chemistry. He enjoys doing the labs and all the problem solving it includes. Ethan is most proud of his growth as a person, student, and athlete throughout high school.

After graduation, Ethan plans to attend college and study Engineering.

Ethan's favorite quote -"I don't know where the limits are, but I would like to go there." - Eliud Kipchoge

Dear ECS Families;

Good afternoon. As we are midway through the second week of what is now a four-week school shutdown, I'm sure that you have many questions.

• When will school restart?
• Will we come back at all this year?
• Will the school year be extended?
• What about graduation?
• Will students be asked to work from home?

The ECS staff, and all districts throughout the State of Michigan, have many of the same questions. Unfortunately as of this moment there are no answers. As a local school district we are planning for many different possible scenarios, however without concrete answers from Lansing we are unable to effectively plan for the future.

Pasted below this message is a copy…

post_text:
Good Morning ECS Families;

As many of you are aware Governor Whitmer just announced a “Stay Home … Stay Safe” executive order effective for the next three weeks starting this evening at midnight. In her public address she indicated that Michigan schools will remain closed through at least Sunday, April 12 in conjunction with the stay at home order. She also indicated that she would be making another announcement in the near future regarding school closures.

Therefore at this point in time, Ellsworth Community School, along with all other K-12 schools in the State of Michigan, will remain closed through at least April 12. We will be sure to let all of our families know ASAP if we receive any additional information.

Thank you for your understanding in these extremely trying times. In the meantime, please stay healthy and stay safe!

Sadie Rosema Esch-Laurent, daughter of Chrissie Esch and Jack Laurent, is the Valedictorian of the class of 2020. Sadie’s hobbies include running, cooking, reading, photography, and working with computers.

Sadie has represented ECS on the Cross Country, Track & Field, Quiz Bowl, and Robotics teams. In addition to this Sadie is a part of the National Honor Society, Student Council, Yearbook, Safe in Northern Michigan, and Little Buddies organizations.

Sadie’s favorite class in Math because it is both challenging and logical. Sadie is most proud of building a computer. After graduation, Sadie plans to attend the University of Michigan to obtain a Bachelor’s Degree in Computer Science.

Sadie's favorite quote -"You may find that having is not so pleasing a thing as wanting. This is not logical, but it is often true." -Mr. Spock, Star Trek

William Jackson Stevens, son of Paula and Dudley Stevens, is a responsible member of the class of 2020.

Bill has represented ECS on the Baseball, Cross Country, and Track & Field teams. In addition, Bill is a part of the Little Buddies mentoring program at ECS. Bill’s hobbies include fishing, hunting, sports and messing around with tractors.

His favorite class is Construction. He likes that it gives an immediate sense of accomplishment. He says that you are able to step back and say, “I just did that”. Bill is most proud of bringing two Baseball Conference Championships to Ellsworth. After graduation, Bill plans to attend Alpena Community College’s Utility Technology Program to become a lineman.

Bill’s favorite quote - “Life is as short as it is precious. You have to live it that way.” - Grandpa Stevens

post_text:
Good Morning Lancers!

It's been quite a surreal last few days. As all of your know, we, along with all other PK-12 schools in Michigan, are currently closed through at least April 6. As a school district we've been focusing on two important tasks since Friday;

(1) Getting a breakfast/lunch meal program up and running to ensure that we are able to keep feeding our students. Our first pickup/delivery will be going out this morning. The sign up form will remain open for upcoming Monday, Wednesday, Friday deliveries.

(2) Putting together voluntary work/activities for students. Paper worksheets and activities are being mailed home this morning and other teachers will be posting lessons and activities.

We'll try to keep our school community as updated as possible via email, Facebook, and the school's notification system.

In the meantime, please stay healthy and stay safe!

We would like to take this time to provide you with some information on questions that we have answers to and to let you know that we will communicate new information as it becomes available.

To begin with, one of our primary concerns as a school district is working to help provide our students and families with breakfast and lunch assistance…

post_text:
Congratulations to the boys and girls cross country teams on their successful seasons.

At the Northern Lakes Conference League Championships both the boys and girls teams finished first. For the boys Robbie Wise, Caleb Godwin, and Ethan Tornga were named first team all conference, while Kolby Krosnicki and Landon Drogt were second team. For the girls, Judy Veldboom, Maia Romeyn, and Avery Strage were first team all conference, while Olivia Strange, Jenna Drenth, Sadie Esch-Laurent, and Lilian Sundstrum were second team.

Then at Saturday's MHSAA Division IV Regional the girls team finished third and qualified for the State Championship meet on Saturday, November 2 in Brooklyn Michigan. Maia Romeyn, Judy Veldboom, and Christy Figueroa were all named to the all regional team. For the boys, Robbie Wise and Caleb Godwin were named to the all region team and also qualified individually for the State Championship.

Calling all Lancers! The fall sports season officially kicks off next week! Please remember, all athletes must have a completed physical form on file in the main school office in order to practice. Here's some information regarding first practice times:

Cross Country: Monday, August 12th from 8:30-10AM (meet at the track)
JV/Varsity Volleyball: Wednesday, August 14th from 5-6:30PM (high school gym)
Football: keep an eye out on the Central Lake/Ellsworth Football page

We're Hiring ...

Ellsworth Community School is seeking a dynamic middle/high school English and History teacher to join our team of educators. The ideal candidate will be passionate about the English language and history and eager to share their knowledge with students. Applicants should also have an engaging personality and be eager to work collaboratively with students, staff, and parents in school related programs both in and out of the classroom.

Vacancy Notice

The following positions are posted for the 2019/20 school year:

Lead GSRP Preschool Teacher – Full Time

Requirements

1. A minimum of a Bachelor’s Degree from an approved college or university and a successful student teaching record.
2. Must have a valid Michigan elementary teaching certificate with either a ZA or ZS endorsement OR possess a bachelor’s degree in Early Childhood.
3. Have knowledge of the growth and development of elementary aged children.
4. Willing to work cooperatively with other teachers and staff as necessary.

Interested applicants must apply in writing to:

Aaron Gaffney, Superintendent
9467 Park Street
Ellsworth, Michigan 49729
Phone: (231) 588-2544
Fax: …

post_text:
The newly renovated ECS elementary baseball field is ready to see its first action tonight. We wish there were before and after pictures we could post, but we failed to get any before starting the project. It's been 18 months in the works, but the results are great. ECS would like to thank the countless people who worked to make this project happen. We're sure we'll miss a few, but we would like to call special attention to the following individuals for their contributions.

ECS Building Trades teachers Brian Certa and Doug Cary, the many students who worked in some capacity on the project over the past two school years, Tex Drenth, Carl Krosnicki, and the Village of Ellsworth for all their time and support, Dudley Stevens for the fantastic concrete work, Doug Nitchman and Atlas Electric for helping with power, the ECS Board of Education for supporting the project, and anyone else who lent a helping hand.

We'd like to wish the Little League teams good luck this season and we sincerely hope you enjoy the field.
